# Chapter 10 — Errors

Every error in Sakura Scheme is a record with fields: `kind`, `message`, `at`, `expected`, `got`, and a `did-you-mean` list. You catch them with `guard`.

## Raise

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(error \"not-enough-fuel\" 'at 'stove)
</pre>

## Guard

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(guard (e ((eq? (error-kind e) 'not-enough-fuel)
           (display \"handled: \") (display (error-message e)) (newline)
           'recovered))
  (error 'not-enough-fuel \"out of gas\"))
</pre>

## Did-you-mean

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(guard (e (#t (error-did-you-mean e)))
  (mpa (lambda (n) (* n 2)) (list 1 2 3)))
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> When I mistype a name — `mpa` for `map` — the runtime doesn't just say \"unknown symbol.\" It offers `did-you-mean: map`. That's the same field a linter would surface. Nothing hidden.

